This is an exam in two parts. Part the first will have you copying and modifying the materials from another groups project (forking and commiting, in git speak). Part the second will have you making a diagram. Because of the unweildy nature of these components, youll be submitting your work by sending me an email that has 1) a link to your forked repository on github and 2) an attachment with your diagram.

Part I: Reproducibility

One of the key tenets of scientific practice is that of a reproducible analysis: that another scientist provided with the same data set should have all of the materials necessary to recreate all plots, tables, and models. Youll be reproducing the analysis of one of the other group projects.

Select one of the following projects as the subject of your replication:

Airbnb in Portland
Extramartial Affairs
College Rankings
Behavior of Red Deer
Hubway Bike Sharing
Technology in the Clinic

The following steps will guide you through setting up your own copy of these materials to work with.

  1. Go to the main repository for the project linked above and click on the fork button, found in the upper right hand corner. If I were looking at the project concerning extramartial affairs, it would look like this:

  1. It may ask you where youd like to fork it to, in which case youll want to choose your personal GitHub account. That will put you to a page that looks like this:

It looks almost the same with one important exception: the previous repository was the original groups project on the classroom account. This is my own private version of the materials that I can do with what I want. To that end

  1. Copy the URL from your forked repo into a new project in RStudio. You should now have access to all of the materials necessary to reproduce their analysis.

Reproducing and extending the analysis

Within your new project, create a fresh .Rmd file called comments.Rmd where youll record your thoughts on their analysis in regard to the following questions.

  1. Is their final report easily reproducible? Essentially, are you able to open their report .Rmd file, knit it, and have it come out looking complete? If not, communicate with the authors so that they can fix it so that it is. You can communicate via email or preferably by writing an issue through GitHub, which can be found at their original repo page in the tab called Issues (its second from left). If you continue to have problems with the reproducibility, please contact me.

  2. Read through their report. What do you think is their strongest finding?

  3. What part of their analysis do you find to be the weakest/most in need of improvement?

  4. As a first trial of your ability to extend their work, pick one of their plots/visualizations and modify it in some way. This can be as superficial as changing the color scheme or the labels. Note that these changes should be done in the original report .Rmd file.

  5. Extending this a bit further, create a new section at the bottom of their report called Extended Analysis. In this section, please extend their analysis in a way that is interesting to you. This could, for example, be fitting an additional model that they havent yet tried, employing a new clustering method, or, say, fitting the same style of classification tree but using a different set of predictors.

Once you are done with these edits to their .Rmd file and your own comments.Rmd, click the checkboxes next to those file names in the Git Pane of RStudio, commit those changes, and push them back your repo on your personal account at Github.

Part II: A whole course in a single picture

This is a very open-ended one. Id like you to use the words below to construct visualization/diagram/flowchart that best represents the field of Statistical Learning as presented in this course. Think carefully about how these concepts are related and how you can encode that structure visually. Youre encouraged to use as many of the words as possible, but can use any format you like, digital or handwritten. If you draw it by hand or sketch it out on your nearest chalkboard, you can take a photo of it. Please submit this photo/file as an attachment in an email to me along with the link to your repo from Part I.

Youre welcome to discuss this part with other students in the class but please include their names in your email.
